Artificial Intelligence – BSc CSIT 4th Semester – Simplified Unit-wise Syllabus

(Note: All unit details are based on the official curriculum and affiliated sources.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit I: Introduction

Understand the concept of Intelligence vs Artificial Intelligence

Explore AI Perspectives:

Acting humanly

Thinking humanly

Acting rationally

Thinking rationally

Review the History of AI

Grasp the Foundations of AI through diverse disciplines:

Philosophy, Economics, Psychology, Sociology, Linguistics, Neuroscience, Mathematics, Computer Science, Control Theory

Discover Applications of AI

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit II: Intelligent Agents

Learn about agents and their structures & properties

Master the PEAS model (Performance measure, Environment, Actuators, Sensors) and agent configuration

Identify agent types:

Simple reflex, Model-based, Goal-based, Utility-based, Learning agents

Study environment classifications:

Deterministic vs Stochastic

Static vs Dynamic

Observable vs Partially Observable

Single-agent vs Multi-agent

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit III: Problem Solving by Searching

Formulate problems using state space, states, and well-defined problem parameters

Compare search strategies, evaluating:

Time and space complexity

Completeness, optimality

Explore Uninformed Search:

DFS, BFS, Depth-limited, Iterative Deepening, Uniform Cost, Bidirectional Search

Dive into Informed Search:

Heuristics, Admissible Heuristics

Greedy Best-First, A*, Hill Climbing, Simulated Annealing

Understand Game-playing via:

Minimax, Alpha-Beta Pruning

Get introduced to Constraint Satisfaction Problems (CSPs)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit IV: Knowledge Representation

Define knowledge and explore knowledge representation systems and their key properties

Learn representation schemes:

Semantic networks, Frames, Conceptual dependencies, Scripts, Rule-based systems

Dive into Propositional Logic:

Syntax, semantics, connectives, truth tables, tautology, validity

Inference methods: Resolution, Forward & Backward Chaining

Master First-order Predicate Logic (FOPL):

Quantification, syntax, semantics, inference using unification & resolution

Explore Uncertain Knowledge:

Random variables, Bayes’ theorem, Bayesian networks

Understand Fuzzy Logic:

Fuzzy sets, membership functions, rule-based systems

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit V: Machine Learning

Grasp learning paradigms: Supervised, Unsupervised, Reinforcement Learning

Study Statistical Learning: Naive Bayes model

Learn Genetic Algorithms: Selection, Crossover, Mutation, Fitness functions

Explore Neural Networks:

Biological vs Artificial, Activation functions (Linear, Step, Sigmoid)

Network types: Feed-forward, Recurrent, Single-layer, Multi-layer

Training methods: Perceptron learning, Backpropagation, Hebbian learning

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit VI: Applications of AI

Expert Systems:

Architecture: Knowledge base, Inference engine, User interface, Working memory

Development process

Natural Language Processing (NLP):

NLU (Understanding) vs NLG (Generation)

NLP pipeline: Lexical, Syntactic, Semantic, Pragmatic analysis

Machine translation fundamentals

Machine Vision:

Concepts, components, and real-world applications

Robotics:

Robot hardware components (sensors, effectors)

Perception mechanisms in robotics

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Overview Table – At a Glance
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit	Core Focus
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
I	AI fundamentals, history, & interdisciplinary roots
II	Intelligent agents and environment modeling
III	Problem-solving via search strategies
IV	Knowledge representation & logical inference
V	Machine learning paradigms and neural networks
VI	Practical AI applications: Expert Systems, NLP, Vision, Robotics
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
